I know.
The economic cost of not closing coal plants by the June 2022 deadline is estimated at NIS 1 billion for 2022, according to a report by the Knesset Research and Information Center.
According to the report, this cost is reflected in the consumer electricity tariff, which is said to be expected to rise in the coming months due to the rise in the price of coal.
In addition, an additional 900,000 tons of coal is expected to be used in 2023, which will result in additional costs to the electricity industry from the continued operation of coal-fired power plants, assuming that the price of natural gas remains significantly lower than the price of coal.
The report said that the NIS 1 billion reduction in electricity rates by 2022 would mean a reduction of about 4 percent in the cost of electricity to households.
In other words, the economic cost of not closing the stations is about $200,000,000, and the total reduction for the household consumer is about 4 percent.
It should be noted that as part of the reform of the electricity sector, it was decided, among other things, to establish a subsidiary of the electricity company, which will establish natural gas-powered units, intended to replace the 4-1 coal units at the Rabin Light Site.
Following this decision, a government decision was adopted in July 2018, stipulating that the 4-1 coal production units at the Oruç Rabin power plant should cease operations.
The decision set timetables, so that the first unit with natural gas will start construction in January 2020 and its operation will start in June 2022, and accordingly the 4-1 coal production units will also cease to operate at that date.
The utility responded: "The fuel policy is written primarily by the Department of Energy.
