State Comptroller's report: The actual budget for most of the years of the Medicare Basket Committee  is less than the recommended budget
According to the report by Matthias Engelmann, for more than 20 years of the Hassel operation, the Ministry of Health did not supervise the activities of the committee.
The report also said that the minutes of meetings are published with a significant delay, if any.
The Ombudsman also recommends that the Subcommittee's activities be made more transparent and that the procedures for the work of the ESC be updated.
Another deficiency found concerns the fact that since the committee began its activities, the Ministry of Health did not ask the hospital funds for reports on the extent of the use and utilization of the drugs that were cancelled, which would have allowed to analyze and control the budget allocated to them.
The Medicare Basket Committee is one of the most influential public committees in our daily lives and our health.
Every year, the commission decides on new drugs that will be given to the public free of charge through the hospital funds  but a new report by the state inspector published today (Tuesday) warns that it has been operating for more than 20 years without control reports on its activities and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council monitoring and examining its activities.
Israel Today correspondent Ren Reznik adds that the state complainant's investigation was conducted following Israel Today's ongoing exposes of drug cartels.
According to the report by Matthew Engelman, it recommends "rectification and improvement in the expansion of the health care basket, leading to better utilization of the health care basket budget to which the public is entitled".
Throughout the years of the existence of the mechanism of the supplement to the drug basket, in the years 2021-1998 drugs were added to the state budget for a total of eight billion NIS, with the supplement moving annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million NIS.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021, applications were submitted to add about 800 new drugs and technologies to the health care basket, with a total annual cost of more than NIS 2 billion.
In practice, the budget allocated to the expansion of the basket was smaller than the scope of the requests.
For most of the committee's existence (90% of the time), the budget surcharge was less than 1.5% of the health care basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired surcharge rate.
The complainant notes that the annual premium needs to be examined and adjusted in order to allow for long-term certainty and planning.
Engelmann also noted that "the transparency model of basketwork is flawed".
For example, the Hassel Committee's working procedure states that minutes of meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the minutes are published with a delay of 160-109 days, while sometimes the minutes of final meetings are not published at all.
"The delay in publishing protocols impairs the transparency of decisions; as a result, the ability of bidders  patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies  to submit re-applications as soon as possible and relevant, after having learned lessons from their bids' postponement, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and amended their bids and reassessed their readiness to accept them in the next round, may be impaired", the reviewer noted in the report.
"The Ministry of Health shall publish the protocols in accordance with the timetables set forth in the protocol".
Of the thousands of submissions, only one economic comment was submitted.
Another criticism of Engelmann concerns the preliminary process of assessing technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The reviewer found that half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for the postponement.
Another discrepancy concerns the activities of the subcommittee of the medicine basket which is closed to the media and the public, and in which patient numbers and drug costs are discussed.
The critic recommends that a public representative be included or that the public debate be made public without any commercial details being kept confidential.
The procedure that the Health Care Basket Committee follows states that "a financial evaluation must be submitted" to a request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic evaluation has been submitted out of thousands of submissions  and the committee makes its decisions without an economic evaluation.
For example, the 2021-2019 Basel Committee hearings had applications to add anti-obesity drugs to the Basel Committee on Medicines and Health's 2021-2019 Basel Committee hearings.
The report found that the requests were not accompanied by economic estimates, including an estimate of the amount that could be saved by reducing the damage of obesity-related diseases or by being able to avoid gastric bypass surgery.
It also appears that the decisions of the Medicines Basket Committee are not in line with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
For example, the Ministry of Health in 2019 defined preventive medicine and the evaluation of the treatment of tumors in chronic diseases as targets, but in the framework of the decisions on the expansion of the basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these targets.
