Medical negligence in the various stages of childbirth
In order to win compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to the negligence, that the damage was caused by the same negligence.
Birth is one of the most joyful and exciting events in a family's life.
But unfortunately, sometimes births end with severe birth or newborn injuries due to the negligence of the medical staff.
In cases where birth has resulted in physical harm to the infant or the mother, there is scope to examine the chain of events that led to the injury and even to consider seeking legal advice.
A medical malpractice lawyer will examine whether there were defects in the conduct of the medical staff at the various stages of birth that caused the damage and, as appropriate, will consult a medical expert in the relevant field.
It should be emphasized that not every error in treatment by the medical staff amounts to negligence (in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily teach that the handling was negligent.
When is it negligence?
When the doctor's error was due to incompetence or deviation from reasonable care, and the incompetence and deviation from accepted care caused harm to the patient that would not have been caused if the doctor had not acted in this way.
In this article, we will examine the different stages of childbirth, explain what complications may occur at each stage, and when they amount to medical negligence.
The junction phase
The fusion phase lasts on average between 8 and 14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix gradually opens (to allow the fetus to pass through at birth) and should eventually reach a diameter of about four inches [10 cm].
Most cases of medical malpractice at the placenta involve the failure to identify fetal distress prior to birth, which has caused damage to the newborn that sometimes manifests itself in cerebral palsy.
Cerebral palsy (CP) is a condition that affects the brain and spinal cord.
Cerebral palsy can be caused by misidentification or delayed identification of congenital breastfeeding, which is manifested by failure to supply oxygen to the fetal brain tissue.
In general, monitoring the newborn's condition and correctly unfolding the monitor that monitors fetal heart activity should lead to early identification of developing fetal distress, allowing the medical team to quickly intervene and rescue the newborn before irreversible damage is done.
Failure to respond to signs of oxygen deprivation, or to interpret data correctly, especially on the fetal monitor, or to respond to distress on the  monitor, may be a sign of negligence.
Cerebral palsy can also be caused by a cord-slip and an undetected uterine rupture.
Even in these extreme events, it's worth checking whether the medical staff acted appropriately.
For example, attorney Anna Reif Ligenza, of the law firm of Sarrur & Co., specializing in representing medical malpractice victims, says that her office handled a lawsuit from a child who was injured during birth after the midwife punctured the amniotic sac when the fetal head was too high, causing the umbilical cord to fall (when the umbilical cord precedes the fetal head) and impaired oxygen supply to the fetal brain (due to pressure from the fetal head on the umbilical cord) and resulting in a child being born with severe neurological damage.
In another case, a lawyer said that her office had filed a lawsuit for gross medical negligence by a staff member in the maternity ward of a large hospital who, during the birth, failed to identify at the time clear signs that would have led to the suspicion that the child was suffering from a rupture of the uterus in the area of the surgical scar of the previous pregnancy.
The fetus that escaped through the rift in its mother's uterus into the womb space suffered severe fetal distress until its late release when it was on the verge of death.
Due to severe fetal distress during his birth the child was left with a complex neurological disability.
We emphasize that in order to win compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal relationship between the negligence of the medical staff that led to the failure to identify the lactating mother and the damage caused to the newborn, that is, that the damage was caused by such negligence and not by any other cause or factor.
The causal relationship will be examined using medical criteria that the medical literature has found to be the only causal relationship between the stroke and the brain injury.
Among other things, the fetus' blood acidity index, its appendix scores, the presence of neurological and systemic damage, and more are tested.
Death of the fetus
The active birth stage
The active stage of labor begins when the cervix opening reaches a diameter of 10 centimeters and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical phase.
Having a baby and avoiding a C-section
In some cases, dysfunctional birth develops, i.e., the lack of progress of the active birth process.
In such cases, a caesarean section is performed to prevent various possible fetal injuries due to delayed delivery.
"There are cases where failure to perform a C-section on time could cause irreversible harm to the fetus", explained lawyer Rafe-Ligonza.
"For example, we have filed a medical malpractice claim of a child's death caused by a significant delay in performing a cesarean section.
Contrary to any accepted medical practice, the medical staff had not been trained to recognize fetal distress and perform a cesarean section despite the extremely slow progress of the birth.
The delay in performing the operation caused extensive systemic damage to Lilouda which eventually led to her death shortly after birth".
Negligence in the birth of a vacuum
In situations where the mother is pregnant or the fetus is in significant danger requiring a particularly rapid termination of the birth, a vacuum birth is sometimes performed.
In this process, a vacuum dome is attached to the fetus' head and the fetus is forcibly pulled out.
This is inherently dangerous and can cause harm to both the fetus and the child, and it requires great care, precision, and skill.
In these cases, medical malpractice may be manifested by the physician not following the mandatory instructions and performing the operation despite the existence of contraindications, such as when the fetal head is too high in the pelvis, or performing it for too long or when despite the failure of several attempts the physician continues and repeats the operation more than the number of attempts allowed.
In these cases if the negligent vacuum operation caused birth defects  among others it could cause cranial damage and bleeding that could cause the development of brain damage  there is room for a damages claim.
Paralysis on the name of ERB
Paralysis of the spine, here's congenital nerve damage in the cervical spine and when it occurs during childbirth it's worth checking to see if the damage was caused by the negligence of the delivery team.
The injury manifests in weakness of the hand muscles and can reach a complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in delivering the newborn due to the occurrence of shoulder fleas - a maternity emergency that whispers when the fetus' shoulders are trapped inside the birth canal after its head has come out.
When should you suspect that the paralysis was caused by medical negligence?
In cases where the fetal weight estimate indicated that the fetus was macrosomal, meaning that it was expected to be born weighing more than 10 pounds (4.5 kg) and according to guidelines it is preferable to deliver the mother by cesarean section.
When the newborn weighs more than 10 pounds, a cesarean section should be considered in light of risk factors including gestational diabetes and prolonged second stage labor.
In the event that the medical team ignores the fetal weight abnormality or other risk factors and chooses to proceed with a vaginal birth and the risk of shoulder dislocation and ERB paralysis is realized, there is a reasonable possibility that medical negligence is involved.
Indeed, in U.S.C. 2694/90 the Supreme Court ruled that "the risk of shoulder deformity during childbirth can be predicted with varying degrees of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder deformity where it is suspected is by cesarean section".
The placenta is released
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its exit occurs due to uterine contractions after the baby's exit and is accompanied by bleeding.
The process usually lasts up to a half hour from the time the baby is delivered and is often spontaneous, without the involvement of the medical staff.
After the discharge, the medical team will check to see if she's completely discharged or if there are any parts of her uterus left.
At this stage, complications can occur that can cause serious damage to the fetus.
One of the most common complications of uterine prolapse is called Ashman's syndrome, a uterine scar caused by inflammation caused by uterine prolapse, a condition that affects the lining of the uterus in a way that prevents pregnancy.
So in cases where the medical team did not identify that she had residual uterine fibroids or did not take all the necessary measures to prevent uterine fibroids from being damaged despite the suspicion of uterine residual uterine fibroids, it may be a case of medical negligence and the case deserves a thorough examination by an experienced lawyer.
Death in childbirth
Maternal death during childbirth is a rather rare occurrence.
In these cases, the event that should have brought happiness and joy to the whole family turns, unfortunately, into the most tragic event for her.
In some cases, the medical team does not detect bleeding in the mother on time or responds late to such bleeding.
"For example", explained Attorney Reif-Ligenza, "our office filed a lawsuit concerning the death of a newborn, in which the medical staff ignored and failed to respond to the worrying vital signs of the newborn for long hours, and later diagnosed massive and uncontrollable bleeding that occurred as a known complication of the underlying disease she suffered from".
"In another case", said Attorney Reif-Ligenza, "our firm represented the relatives of a woman who died after giving birth to twins due to bleeding from an improperly sutured caesarean section.
In the same case, the woman complained of severe pain and weakness after the operation, but the medical staff did not properly address her complaints and her clinical condition, responding only after her body systems began to collapse, which led to her death".
Loss of uterus
In severe cases, medical negligence at birth can lead to a hysterectomy, says lawyer Rafe Lingza: "Our office has filed a lawsuit against a hospital that performed a hysterectomy because of medical negligence after birth.
In that case the mother, a young woman of 31, lost her uterus due to inadequate treatment of massive bleeding observed by the medical staff after birth and yet no timely action was taken that could have prevented the damage".
What are the damages awarded in medical malpractice at birth?
Maternity compensation for injury due to medical negligence at birth includes many damage components, with the most significant amounts being for pain and suffering, nursing and paid care, loss of wages and pension to the injured and even to his parents and other damage components.
Compensation paid to an injured minor for lost wages and pensions is calculated in most cases on the basis of the average wage in the economy.
Also, the compensation includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitation equipment, the cost of adapting the home to the needs of the baby, mobility and more.
"The amount of compensation was determined in each case for his body and according to his circumstances", says lawyer Reif-Ligenza. She adds that "today most medical malpractice claims end in a settlement that weighs the chance and risk that each party has in the management of the procedure", but she added that "there are cases where the procedure ends only in a judgment, which then if the claim is not rejected, the claimants will receive full compensation for all their damages and for example, in a lawsuit conducted by our office, the district court ruled for a minor who suffered a cerebral palsy due to a delay in seeing a distress settlement. The compensation exceeds ten million shekels".
In conclusion
Medical malpractice at birth is undoubtedly every family's nightmare.
In these cases, a proper judicial review of the chain of events that led to the tragic outcome, by a lawyer trained in handling medical malpractice claims, can help you get the compensation you deserve.
