Expert: "It may be that in any sector with a lot of cousin marriages, there is a high incidence of the disease".
Keratoconus is an inherited eye disease that causes some visual impairment.
It's very important to diagnose it early, and find the right solutions to prevent it from getting worse.
In recent years, some studies have been conducted to help understand how the disease develops, and new treatments have been developed.
The new studies provide a scientific basis for suspecting that Keratoconus eye disease is a genetic disease.
A recent study that looked at the shape of the cornea from dome to cone found that the cause of corneal disease and weakness and deformation is related to an enzyme imbalance, where free radicals can damage proteins in the cornea - and its structure changes.
The source of that enzyme deficiency is genetic, a fact that supports the hypothesis that keratoconus is an inherited disease.
According to Prof. Ariella Gordon-Shag, head of the Department of Optometry Sciences at Hadassah Academic College, "In a study published in the field among Arab students in Haifa, the prevalence of keratoconus was found to be 3.2%.
The highest prevalence was among students from the Bedouin sect - 20% had karatokonos, but there was a relatively small sample".
The researcher added that this is not a surprising finding: "Cartoconus is very common in the Bedouin sector.
In our studies, we found that consanguineous marriages are a risk factor for cartoconus.
So in any sector with a lot of cousin marriages, you might find a high incidence".
In this context, it should be noted that this is an important finding in light of the unambiguous conclusion: in cases where there is a family history of cartoconus disease, all family members should undergo an appropriate eye examination as soon as possible.
According to Erza Procter, a clinical optometrist B.Sc., "there is ten times more clinic turnover from remote peripheral areas, mainly from the south, compared to the center".
Procter adds that "in the last decade I have noticed that most patients are moving from the periphery, especially from the Beersheba area.
This is mainly due to the high prevalence of inter-family marriage (especially in the Bedouin sector) and various allergies, and lack of awareness of proper treatment of the problem".
So how do you diagnose the disease?
Procter explains that keratoconus usually develops in adolescence or late teens (ages 16-15, or 20).
