Research says that zooming in on meetings hurts creativity.
Some 2,100 engineers and academics worldwide were asked to develop solutions to the problem  some in video conferences, some in face-to-face meetings •
The result: Virtual dating hurts creativity and thinking outside the box
The study's lead author, Columbia University, says that "visual focus on the screen impairs the process of generating ideas".
There's no impairment in productivity or critical thinking.
A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature looked at the impact of video conferencing on participants' creativity, compared to face-to-face meetings.
Unfortunately, we've found that creativity is actually being hurt in virtual meetings through screens.
The question of the study -- led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University -- was whether remote computer meetings preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming meetings, or whether creativity and free thinking decline as a result of the distance.
The study itself started as early as 2016, but got a big boost in the two years of the coronavirus, when many workers moved to work from home.
"People in a face-to-face meeting move around the room, use objects, and are helped to think creatively", says Brooks.
"In a computer meeting, however, the focus on maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative brain activity.
Visual focus on the screen is impairing cognition.
People are more focused on video when they're interacting, which hurts the broad, expansive idea-making process".
Space is shrinking.
To test the results and see if they would repeat themselves, they were tested twice -- once at Columbia University and once in real life -- on engineers who had known each other from early on.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty and students into two parts - one where the subjects were asked to meet in person and develop solutions to a problem, and the other where they were asked to do it via computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to split up similarly and solve a problem presented to them in a new way.
In both cases, there was a decrease in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking among those who met virtually on video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher on ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
He thinks that in thinking, people often look at their environment to help generate ideas, whereas in video conferencing, thinking is focused on the screen and doesn't expand in a creative way.
"When people in the same room look around and see the space, there are objects and situations that can trigger new associations in them.
"In contrast, research shows that interacting with computers changes our attention so that we are more inward-looking and screen-focused, and this reduces innovation and idea generation through looking at the environment and thinking outward".
There's no harm in critical thinking.
However, before managers rush workers back to the office, the researchers note that "Computing did not impair productivity itself nor did it impair people's critical thinking about innovative proposals, where they had to pick the best idea from a set of ideas.
That is, the harm is focused on creativity alone and not on other forms of computer work".
Professor Ellen Langer, a psychology professor at Harvard University, also cites the findings.
She says, "There's a difference between just being creative, like new uses for Prisby, and working solutions.
It may also be that when employees are more relaxed after introductions, or when they work from home, creativity does improve".
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson also proposed a future study in which such meetings would be reduced to thinking and wandering around the room to see how this activity would affect the end result.
Dr. Olson also suggested that following the study only brainstorming sessions would return employees to work and as a rule he suggested not to be alarmed by one study but to conduct another investigation in the field.
"I wouldn't want workers to be forced back and not be happy. That's a bigger insult", he says.
