A new global study predicts a significant decline in the next 25 years
The Solution: Proper Management of Water
A disturbing new study recently published in the journal Earth's Future predicts that by 2050, the amount of water available for agriculture will decline by about 80 percent if the rate of water consumption and population growth in the world remains at their current use trends.
In the study, which involved scientists from all the world's science agencies, scientists aggregated the total amount of rainwater, rivers and freshwater sources in the world and compared it to humanity's need for agriculture.
The dismal findings of the study show that right now the rate of water consumption has been doubling repeatedly over the past 10 years, while global warming is causing reduced rainfall in agricultural areas around the world.
According to the study, 84 percent of the world's arable land will experience severe rainwater shortages.
One of the key findings of the study calls on farmers around the world to adapt their farming to climate change and seasonal changes, and to switch to farming methods that take into account the water that enters the soil to avoid the evaporation process that leads to widespread waste of rainwater.
The researchers also recommend that farmers working near saltwater sources use rainwater harvesting technologies to prevent rainwater from flowing into the sea.
