We looked at what the side effects of the coronavirus vaccine were.
Many people who inject feel weak, hot and tired after receiving the injection, while others do not.
Could this indicate a stronger immune system in those who do experience these effects, or is this just a baseless rumor?
As more and more people are being screened, the lack of information about side effects continues to confuse and create rumors, most of which are not true.
Are the immune systems of those who developed side effects stronger than those whose bodies responded less severely to the vaccine, which might prove that their systems are unable to fight off an invading foreign body?
"There are several levels of vaccine reactions", says Dr. David Devere, head of the hospital's primary care unit and a member of the CDC (Covid-19 Disease Control and Prevention) Advisory Committee, and he reassures: "Headaches, fatigue, aching joints, these are the immediate reactions of the immune system.
This is how the body responds to the entry of a foreign body into the system".
Is there a link between the levels of antibodies that develop and the side effects?
"There is no correlation between sensations and development of antibodies to the virus.
About 60 to 50 percent experience side effects, but about 90 percent develop immunity to the virus.
People who developed stronger responses were not found to be more protected".
"There is no correlation in the medical literature between immediate response and vaccine levels.
In some of the trials where people also got placebo vaccines, about a quarter of them developed headaches.
It's also a psychological component -- how a person perceives the vaccine, if they expect to have side effects.
Many of the cold events could have happened in a normal way, but because the public is immune, they attribute the response to the vaccine itself, and that's the bias we see with vaccines in general - attribution of cold events to and in proximity to the vaccine".
