The Privacy Commissioner claims that the Eretz Road Company violated the Privacy Act and its regulations.
After a report that a company, the Israel Highway 6 operator, had been notified of a security incident that occurred at the company, the Privacy Protection Authority initiated an enforcement procedure.
During the event, a security vulnerability was discovered on its payment site, which allowed the disclosure of a large amount of information from the accounts of the member's customers, which were exposed to all eyes.
Among other things, the payment accounts of customers over a period of time were exposed and these accounts included personal information, including first and last name, payment amounts, vehicle location, travel dates and times.
Furthermore, since the company did not document access to its systems as required by law, it is not possible to know precisely for how long unauthorized parties could have accessed the company's systems.
In the letter of infringement, which the Privacy Authority forwarded to the company, the Authority emphasized that most companies and large organizations in the economy are required to adopt a dynamic information security policy, and that with the development of threats and risks, the organization has an obligation to carefully examine the updated risks and act in accordance with the update of the security measures accepted in the circumstances of the case, depending on the nature of the database and its quality.
As a result, companies and organizations are required to update their systems and conduct risk assessments and penetration tests to examine and assess changing risks.
Companies and organisations are also required to use an automated recording mechanism and to provide training to employees, in accordance with the provisions of the Privacy (Information Security) Regulations.
In accordance with the findings of the audit, the Authority determined that the company had violated the provisions of the Privacy Protection Act and its regulations and required the company to take a number of corrective actions.
"The matter has been handled in accordance with the strictest requirements".
